<A name=Filtering_white_noise></A><A name=Filteringwhitenoise></A><span class=moyet>==</span><span class=blogtitle><b>Filtering white noise</b></span><span class=moyet>==</span>

<p>

I just posted how to generate a white noise .wav file in Linux.  Here's how to take a file with random bytes and make a interesting ocean-like sound from it:

<p>

<tt>sox --channels=2 --encoding=ms-adpcm -b 16 -r 44100 -s whitenoise.raw oceannoise.wav gain -12 band -n 1200 200 phaser 0.7 0.7 .1 0.5 0.1 -s reverb</tt><br>

<p>

Or for something more windlike:

<p>

<tt>sox --channels=2 --encoding=ms-adpcm -b 16 -r 44100 -s whitenoise.raw windnoise.wav gain -12 band -n 800 200 phaser 0.5 0.5 .1 0.5 0.1 -s echos 0.3 0.3 187 0.2 83 0.2 131 0.2 1024 0.3 reverb</tt><br>

<p>

(My wife says this second incantation sounds like street traffic)

<p>

These incantations is based on the command line posted here:

<p>

<blockquote>
<A href="http://unreasonable.org/node/303">http:/<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>/unreasonable<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>.org<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>/node<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>/303</A>
</blockquote>

(Note that those Sox settings do not generate true pink noise)

<p>

It‚Äôs also possible to download white noise files for free here:

<p>

<blockquote>
<A href="https://archive.org/details/TenMinutesOfWhiteNoisePinkNoiseAndBrownianNoise">https:/<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>/<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>archive.<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>org/<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>details/<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>Ten<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>Minutes<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>Of<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>White<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>Noise<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>Pink<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>Noise<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>And<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>Brownian<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>Noise</A>
