<A name=How_to_make_white_noise></A><A name=Howtomakewhitenoise></A><span class=moyet>==</span><span class=blogtitle><b>How to make white noise</b></span><span class=moyet>==</span>

<p>

To generate white noise is a two-step process.

<p>

The first step is to generate a random file.  This can be done, in Linux, with 

<p>

<tt>cat /dev/urandom &gt; whitenoise.raw</tt><br>

<p>

Or, using the rg32-bin tool available at <A href="http://samiam.org/rg32">http:/<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>/samiam<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>.org<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>/rg32</A>

<p>

<tt>rg32-bin '' &gt; whitenoise.raw</tt><br>

<p>

In both cases, terminate the process after a few seconds with Ctrl-C (hit the "Ctrl" and the "C" keys at the same time)

<p>

Sox, which is included with CentOS 6, can then make this file an audio file:

<p>

<tt>sox --channels=2 --encoding=ms-adpcm -b 16 -r 44100 -s whitenoise.raw whitenoise.wav gain -6</tt><br>

<p>

We add the ‚Äúgain -6‚Äù so that the file does not distort.

