<p>

The reason I like to post here on my microblog instead of some big corporate website (Facebook, Twitter, etc.) or online community is became I‚Äôm the one who gets the ad revenue should something here go viral:

<p>

<blockquote>
<A href="http://www.codinghorror.com/blog/2009/08/are-you-a-digital-sharecropper.html">http:/<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>/<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>www.<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>codinghorror.<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>com/<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>blog/<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>2009/<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>08/<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>are-<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>you-<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>a-<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>digital-<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>sharecropper.<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>html</A>
</blockquote>

I don‚Äôt mind my occasional contribution to Wikipedia since they are strictly ad-free, and since anything there is released under an open license.

<p>

I also don‚Äôt mind using Facebook to share a photo with old acquaintances or using Twitter to have some level of contact with actors in the Mexican 
<i>telenovelas</i>
that I watch.  But anything substantial is here on my own webpage. 

<p>

The reason I no longer get too involved with online communities is because it‚Äôs just too much work for what amounts to nothing more than a virtual pat on the back, and because web-1.0 style online communities get really angry really quickly at any attempt to make money from one‚Äôs hard work.

<p>

‚ÄúDigital sharecropping‚Äù can also refer to programmers whose revenue stream is tightly controlled by another company, such as the companies making games for Facebook or people whose income comes from selling iPhone apps.  

<p>

